## Q5 — Reference site UX patterns (from Gibson Dunn + Quinn Emanuel)

**Nav structure (adopt this):**
```
[Logo]  Practice Areas | Attorneys | Insights | About | Locations  [Search] [Contact CTA]
```
Desktop: horizontal, minimal, uppercase or smallcaps labels, no mega-menus.
Mobile: hamburger → full-screen overlay with language switcher visible.

**Hero section:**
- Full-viewport-height editorial image (B&W or desaturated) with cinematic overlay
- One large serif headline (60–80px), subhead 18px, single gold CTA button
- Optional: subtle parallax scroll or looping B&W video background at low opacity

**Practice area page layout:**
- Full-width header with practice name + gold accent rule
- Left rail: alphabetical list of sub-practices (sticky)
- Main content: rich prose, key contacts cards (attorney photo + name + title),
  recent matters/results section (brief 2-line summaries), related insights feed

**Publications / Insights listing:**
- Masonry or even 3-column grid of cards
- Each card: category tag (gold label), headline, date, attorney byline, 1-line
  excerpt, "Read more" link
- Filter bar: All | Client Alerts | Articles | In the Media | Firm News

**Attorney profile:**
- Hero: full-bleed B&W portrait, name in large serif, title + practice areas
- Body: bio prose, representative matters, publications list, contact block

---

## Q6 — WebLLM vs transformers.js (final decision)

**Use WebLLM (`@mlc-ai/web-llm`).**

Decision rationale:
- The brief requires chat/text generation with a reflection+evaluation agentic loop.
  WebLLM's OpenAI-compatible API (`engine.chat.completions.create`) maps directly
  onto a multi-turn conversation array — straightforward to implement the
  generate → reflect → evaluate → answer cycle.
- WebLLM streams tokens natively; transformers.js text generation is harder to
  stream and lacks a clean conversational API for multi-turn.
- transformers.js excels at embeddings, classification, and HF pipeline tasks —
  none of which are in scope here.
- WebLLM's WebWorkerMLCEngine keeps the Angular UI thread free during inference.

Agentic loop implementation sketch:
```
user query
  → [GENERATE] engine.chat({role:'user', ...}) — initial answer draft
  → [REFLECT]  engine.chat({role:'assistant', draft}, {role:'user', reflectPrompt}) — self-critique
  → [EVALUATE] parse evaluation score from reflection output against rubric
  → if score < threshold: loop back to GENERATE with reflection as context (max 2 retries)
  → else: emit final answer to UI
```
Rubric for evaluation (inject in system prompt): accuracy, completeness,
appropriate legal caution, citation of practice area context.

